resource.http://dev.llgc.org.uk/sas/full_text: The making of the prints is done in several steps. First of all, Hokusai drew on a sheet of paper the motifs of his series on the thirty-six Views of Mount Fuji. Then, he traced his drawings on wood to be able to engrave them. After that, he painted his wood with two or three colors, as was the custom in Japan at the time. Finally, he proceeded to printing. The sidebar with the information of prints and signature are also engraved on wood.The size of this print is: length of 248 mm and width of 369 mm.
resource.chars:
The making of the prints is done in several steps. First of all, Hokusai drew on a sheet of paper the motifs of his series on the thirty-six Views of Mount Fuji. Then, he traced his drawings on wood to be able to engrave them. After that, he painted his wood with two or three colors, as was the custom in Japan at the time. Finally, he proceeded to printing. The sidebar with the information of prints and signature are also engraved on wood.


The size of this print is: length of 248 mm and width of 369 mm.

resource.http://dev.llgc.org.uk/sas/full_text: Hokusai uses color to create contrast in his prints. In this one, the foreground with the fisherman is rich in color and contrasts with the background which is marked by a dominance of white. The three colors used for this print are the green, the blue and the red. Furthermore, there is two shades of green and blue. Colors and their shades bring movement and depict life (people, see and plants). In contrast, the white of the background represents emptiness and immobility.

Hokusai uses color to create contrast in his prints. In this one, the foreground with the fisherman is rich in color and contrasts with the background which is marked by a dominance of white.
